"{\"abstract\":\"This work concerns the mechanism design for online scheduling in a strategic setting. In this setting, each job is owned by a self-interested agent who may misreport the release time, deadline, length, and value of her job, while we need to determine not only the schedule of the jobs, but also the payment of each agent. We focus on the design of incentive compatible (IC) mechanisms, and study the maximization of social welfare (i.e., the aggregated value of completed jobs) by competitive analysis. We first derive two lower bounds on the competitive ratio of any deterministic IC mechanism to characterize the landscape of our research: one bound is 5, which holds for equallength jobs; the other bound is \\u03ba ln\\u03ba + 1 \\u2212 o(1), which holds for unequal-length jobs, where \\u03ba is the maximum ratio between lengths of any two jobs. We then propose a deterministic IC mechanism and show that such a simple mechanism works very well for two models: (1) In the preemption-restart model, the mechanism can achieve the optimal competitive ratio of 5 for equal-length jobs and a near optimal ratio of ( 1 (1\\u2212 )2 + o(1)) \\u03ba ln\\u03ba for unequal-length jobs, where 0 < < 1 is a small constant; (2) In the preemption-resume model, the mechanism can achieve the optimal competitive ratio of 5 for equal-length jobs and a near optimal competitive ratio (within factor 2) for unequallength jobs.\",\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"1705507\",\"name\":\"Xujin Chen\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1705507\"},{\"authorId\":\"33633487\",\"name\":\"X. Hu\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/33633487\"},{\"authorId\":\"152998017\",\"name\":\"T. Liu\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/152998017\"},{\"authorId\":\"3029546\",\"name\":\"Weidong Ma\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/3029546\"},{\"authorId\":\"143826491\",\"name\":\"T. Qin\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1